her body prepared. &quot;DVinn had better be right about this one,&quot; she thought. The Ambassador, her sometimes lover, sometimes slave, and long time business partner<br>
had sent her to Shadow Haven to intercept a courier bringing information to the Koada'Dal. DVinn had only mentioned that the message involved a sect of Innoruuk's followers, but had offered her a substantial sum to retrieve it.<br>
<br>
Staring intently into a small piece of broken mirrored glass, she watched the reflection of the hallway until she saw a man with a leather satchel approaching, making his way towards the tunnel that led to the Nexus. A Fier'Dal, and by the look of him, a filthy tree hugger and lover of bears.<br>
She smiled to herself, hand light on the ebony hilt of her dagger. She counted the footfalls.<br>
<br>
The last thing the courier saw was a flash of raven hair as a knife split his spine and pierced his heart. As darkness fell upon him, he thought he heard laughter..<br>
<br>
Innet T'Verin chuckled quietly as she propped up the limp elf against the wall of her alcove. She quickly removed a sheaf of documents from the satchel and wiped the blood off her blade. Slipping out of the alcove, she quickly made her way out of Shadow Haven and back through the Nexus to the small cave that she occasionally inhabited near the ruins of the Combine outpost of Kunark.<br>
<br>
Safely back in her cave, she lit a small fire, and began to read the sheaf of papers liberated from the courier. Her dark eyes grew wide and the mouthful of Grimling jerky she'd been chewing was quickly forgotten as she read:<br>
<br>
        &quot;General Jyleel,<br>
<br>
        I regret to bring you disturbing news from the front. Some time ago, as you may recall, we discovered a cult of Tier'Dal claiming credit for the many atrocities comitted in the common lands. This cult, 'harvesters' as they call themselves, has been steadily gaining power both in Neriak and throughout the loosly defined collective of the followers of Innoruuk.<br>
<br>
        We now believe that it was an agent of these Harvesters who was responsible for the failed attempt on Kolvaran Angelborn's life some months ago.<br>
<br>
        ...<br>
<br>
Innet made an odd squeaking noise as she indignantly inhaled grimling jerky. &quot;That goody bastard was mine!&quot; she coughed, recovering her breath. &quot;I would have had him if it hadn't been for that traitorous wretch Sendariu,&quot; she muttered. Maybe better to let these Harvesters take the blame for that one... She hadn't expected an attack from one of her Tier'dal sisters, and it had ruined a perfectly good assassination. Taking a large swig of ale, she continued reading:<br>
<br>
        ...<br>
<br>
<br>
        &quot;According to our intelligence reports, the harvesters believe that by slaying all those who oppose Innoruuk, they can pave the way for the prince of hate to shape the world in his own twisted image.&quot;<br>
<br>
        ...<br>
<br>
Innet smiled wryly. &quot;These must be the people that fool Lanys T'Vyl kept shouting about,&quot; she muttered. She had a hunch these harvesters were responsible for quite a bit of the competition in her line of work. Not surprising, seeing as how their objectives appeared to be largely similar.<br>
<br>
        ...<br>
<br>
        &quot;While we continue to investigate further, it is the feeling of myself and of Regent Rohwin Amore-Ardour that Felwithe should begin preparations of defense against this cult. Based on activity in the region, I can predict that these people will only grow in power and influence among the shadier sides of Norrath. We suspect that they will begin mounting larger offensives soon, and we have unsubstantiated reports that they have already begun to defile our lady Tunare's own gardens in the Plane of Growth.<br>
<br>
        I shall return to Felwithe soon to speak of this to the Council. Until then, may Tunare keep you and guide you.<br>
<br>
        Elyar Klennix, Vice Regent of Cursus Honorum<br>
&quot;<br>
<br>
        ...<br>
<br>
Innet rolled up the papers, shoved them in a tube, and reached for another ale. Her fourth, she noted absently. Pacing back and forth in the cold cave, her mind ran with questions. Who were these harvesters? Could they really<br>
be doing His work in preparation for His coming? Not even the clerics of Neriak acted with that much fervor, a fact that had disgusted her. The politics of Neriak had become so muddled that she had been forced to kill several minor politicians and one major out of sheer fury. The guards,<br>
clearly no longer following the path of righteous hate, pursued her through the mountains before she was forced to take refuge with the Widowmistress. Innet's fingers ran over the cool hilt of the dagger that the Widowmistress had given her, the same blade that had slain the courier and so many more who stood in Father's path. Her decision was made.<br>
<br>
&quot;I must seek out these harvesters, to find out if they truly follow the chosen path of Innoruuk..&quot; Innet quickly packed a rucksack and, message tube in hand, began to make her way towards the commonlands to try and locate the harvesters.<br>
<br>
Innet T'Verin<br>
